<DOC><DOCNO> ZF32-113-161 </DOCNO><DOCID>11 045 467</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computer Graphics World  July 1991 v14 n7 p119(3).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>MGM on the desktop? (Software Review) (Mediamaker) (evaluation)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Schaff, Robert.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Mediamaker from Macromind Inc is an impressive first effort incombining consumer market video technology with the AppleMacintosh, but it is expensive.andP;  Mediamaker itself costs only$695, but a considerable amount of video gear is necessary whichcosts a minimum of $5,000.andP;  Mediamaker supplies most of thefunctionality of the central edit controller in a traditionalvideo production suite and permits users to shoot, edit, andproduce cinematic material.andP;  Mediamaker is easy to install, butusers should expect to do some troubleshooting.andP;  The biggestadvantage of using Mediamaker is its print-to-video capability.andO;Users can use Medimaker to cue and record intermixed video andgraphics on a destination VTR or camcorder.andP;  Problems include lackof control over the destination or recording VTR, no easy way toplay back a sequence just recorded, screen formatting andwindowing anomalies, incompatability with some desk accessories,and registration of CD-audio elements across video transitions isnot perfect.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Company:   MacroMind Inc. (Products).andO;Product:   Apple Macintosh (Microcomputer) (evaluation)MediaMaker (Multimedia software) (evaluation).andO;Topic:     Multimedia softwareEvaluationSoftware packagesComputer GraphicsDesktop VideoVideo SystemsFilm Recorders.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>